  <div id="integrating-google-location-history" class="section level2">
    <h2>
      Integrating Google location history
    </h2>
    
    <p>
      This blog is a continuation of <a href="https://www.harshaash.com/in-time-problem">in-time analysis problem</a>. I want to analyse my entry time at office and understand what factors effect it.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      I want to integrate my Google Location history to my analysis. This to find the factors<br /> 1. Travel time<br /> 2. Mode of transportation
    </p>
    
    <p>
      It’s no secret that Google stores a data on all of us. But at least they allow us to access quite a lot of the data they have collected on us. Among this is the Google location history.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The Google location history can be downloaded from your Google account under <a href="https://takeout.google.com/settings/takeout" class="uri">https://takeout.google.com/settings/takeout</a>. I have only selected “location history” for download, otherwise it will take super long to get all my Google data.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      The downloaded data is a .json file and can be loaded with the jsonlite package. Loading this file into R might take a few minutes because it can be quite big, depending on how many location points Google had saved.
    </p>
    
    <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">&lt;span class="hljs-keyword">library&lt;/span>(jsonlite)
system.time(
  x &lt;- fromJSON(&lt;span class="hljs-string">"Takeout/Location History/Location History.json"&lt;/span>)
)</code></pre>
    
    <pre><code class="hljs">##    user  system elapsed 
##   42.33    0.94   43.68</code></pre>
    
    <p>
      Converting to data frame
    </p>
    
    <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">locations &lt;- as.data.frame(x$locations)
dplyr::sample_n(locations, &lt;span class="hljs-number">5&lt;/span>)</code></pre>
    
    <pre><code class="hljs">##          timestampMs latitudeE7 longitudeE7 accuracy
## 103365 1536096790010  129768902   777331000       26
## 35910  1540915392804  129831967   777385539       25
## 122524 1533614092634  129768885   777331206       24
## 250121 1514781948632  129762573   777340167       30
## 172682 1526581945449  129768248   777331578       26
##                                                                                                                                                              activity
## 103365                                                                                                                                                           NULL
## 35910                                                                                                                                                            NULL
## 122524                                                                                                                                                           NULL
## 250121                                                                                                                                                           NULL
## 172682 1526581948974, STILL, IN_VEHICLE, IN_ROAD_VEHICLE, UNKNOWN, UNKNOWN, ON_FOOT, WALKING, IN_RAIL_VEHICLE, UNKNOWN, ON_BICYCLE, 61, 26, 26, 13, 13, 5, 5, 4, 3, 1
##        altitude verticalAccuracy velocity heading
## 103365       NA               NA       NA      NA
## 35910        NA               NA       NA      NA
## 122524       NA               NA       NA      NA
## 250121       NA               NA       NA      NA
## 172682       NA               NA       NA      NA</code></pre>
    
    <p>
      The date and time column is in the POSIX milliseconds format, so I converted it to human readable format.
    </p>
    
    <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">&lt;span class="hljs-comment"># The Unix epoch is 1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC*&lt;/span>
locations$time &lt;- as.POSIXct(as.numeric(locations$timestampMs)/&lt;span class="hljs-number">1000&lt;/span>, origin = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"1970-01-01"&lt;/span>)</code></pre>
    
    <p>
      Similarly, longitude and latitude are saved in 10^7 format and were converted to GPS coordinates.
    </p>
    
    <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">locations$lat = locations$latitudeE7 / &lt;span class="hljs-number">1e7&lt;/span>
locations$lon = locations$longitudeE7 / &lt;span class="hljs-number">1e7&lt;/span></code></pre>
    
    <p>
      The modified dataFrame will look like this
    </p>
    
    <pre><code class="hljs">##                       time      lat      lon accuracy
## 52943  2018-10-15 20:35:10 12.98313 77.73848       25
## 261208 2017-12-10 01:28:14 12.97703 77.73333       20
## 222407 2018-02-20 11:54:46 12.97704 77.73311       23
## 31771  2018-11-04 20:15:41 12.97459 77.75759       16
## 135606 2018-07-18 22:39:30 12.98714 77.73598       26
##                           activity
## 52943                         NULL
## 261208                        NULL
## 222407 1519107857104, TILTING, 100
## 31771    1541342741418, STILL, 100
## 135606                        NULL</code></pre>
    
    <div id="data-stats" class="section level3">
      <h3>
        Data stats
      </h3>
      
      <p>
        Before I get to actually plotting maps, I want to explore a few basic statistics of the data.<br /> 1. How many data points did Google record over what period of time?
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">nrow(locations)</code></pre>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">## [1] 268248</code></pre>
      
      <ol start="2" style="list-style-type: decimal">
        <li>
          From when till when is this data recorded
        </li>
      </ol>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">min(locations$time)</code></pre>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">## [1] "2017-11-22 13:20:07 IST"</code></pre>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">max(locations$time)</code></pre>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">## [1] "2018-12-05 15:14:54 IST"</code></pre>
      
      <ol start="3" style="list-style-type: decimal">
        <li>
          How many days were recorded?
        </li>
      </ol>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">length(unique(date(locations$time)))</code></pre>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">## [1] 379</code></pre>
    </div>
    
    <div id="integrating-with-attendence-data-set" class="section level3">
      <h3>
        Integrating with attendance data set
      </h3>
      
      <p>
        The data set contains the time when I swiped into office and the time when I swiped out of office. Data from 4th October 2017 to 29th November 2018 is considered. For more details on attendance data set, please <a href="https://www.harshaash.com/univariate-analysis/">read here</a>
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Finding how many working days are captured in Google Maps.
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">working_days &lt;- locations %&gt;% 
  filter((date(time) %&lt;span class="hljs-keyword">in&lt;/span>% date(attendance$Attendance.Date)))
length(unique(date(working_days$time)))</code></pre>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">## [1] 246</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        A total of 246 working days were captured of 266 working days.
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">&lt;span class="hljs-keyword">library&lt;/span>(ggmap)
qmplot(lon, lat, data = working_days,zoom = &lt;span class="hljs-number">5&lt;/span>)</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Filtering for data for Bangalore
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">&lt;span class="hljs-comment"># Bangalore North Eastern border is 13.071393, 77.787015 (Hoskote)&lt;/span>
&lt;span class="hljs-comment"># Bangalore South Western border is 12.889629, 77.454102 (Kumbalgodu)&lt;/span>
bangalore &lt;- locations %&gt;% filter(lon &lt; &lt;span class="hljs-number">77.787015&lt;/span>, lon &gt; &lt;span class="hljs-number">77.454102&lt;/span>, lat &lt; &lt;span class="hljs-number">13.071393&lt;/span>,lat &gt; &lt;span class="hljs-number">12.889629&lt;/span> )
qmplot(lon, lat, data = bangalore, geom = c(&lt;span class="hljs-string">"point"&lt;/span>,&lt;span class="hljs-string">"density2d"&lt;/span>))</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Considering only the time when I will be leaving the house<br /> out.of.house.time = Clustering the longitudes and latitudes near my house. Then finding the maximum time (before the office in time) when I was in this cluster.<br /> in.time = office in time taken from attendance data set
      </p>
      
      <p>
        travelling.time = out.of.house.time &#8211; in.time
      </p>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">##           date travelling.time
## 124 2018-06-04   2823.197 secs
## 168 2018-08-09   1347.491 secs
## 70  2018-03-13   1266.811 secs
## 194 2018-09-24   1038.792 secs
## 74  2018-03-19    791.593 secs</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        Plotting histogram of travel time
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">ggplot(travel,aes(x = as.numeric(travelling.time))) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins = &lt;span class="hljs-number">50&lt;/span>, fill = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"cornflowerblue"&lt;/span>, alpha = &lt;span class="hljs-number">0.8&lt;/span>) +
  labs(x = &lt;span class="hljs-string">'Travel Time (seconds)'&lt;/span>, y=&lt;span class="hljs-string">'Density'&lt;/span>, title = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"Travel time"&lt;/span>) +
  theme_minimal()</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
      </p>
    </div>
    
    <div id="mode-of-transport" class="section level3">
      <h3>
        Mode of transport
      </h3>
      
      <p>
        Google also guesses my activity based on distance traveled per time.<br /> In the Bangalore data frame, the column activity has activities data.<br /> Removing null values and creating a data frame for activities (in Bangalore)<br /> Capturing the activity in main_activity
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">activities &lt;- bangalore$activity

list.condition &lt;- sapply(activities, &lt;span class="hljs-keyword">function&lt;/span>(x) !is.null(x[[&lt;span class="hljs-number">1&lt;/span>]]))

activities  &lt;- activities[list.condition]

activities.df &lt;- do.call(&lt;span class="hljs-string">"rbind"&lt;/span>, activities)

activities.df &lt;- activities.df %&gt;%
  mutate(main_activity = sapply(activity, &lt;span class="hljs-keyword">function&lt;/span>(x) x[[&lt;span class="hljs-number">1&lt;/span>]][&lt;span class="hljs-number">1&lt;/span>][[&lt;span class="hljs-number">1&lt;/span>]][&lt;span class="hljs-number">1&lt;/span>]),
         time = as.POSIXct(as.numeric(timestampMs)/&lt;span class="hljs-number">1000&lt;/span>, origin = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"1970-01-01"&lt;/span>)) %&gt;% 
  dplyr::select(time, main_activity)
dplyr::sample_n(activities.df, &lt;span class="hljs-number">5&lt;/span>)</code></pre>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">##                      time main_activity
## 31039 2018-08-17 11:57:32    IN_VEHICLE
## 13259 2018-10-09 09:35:16       TILTING
## 40059 2018-07-17 11:41:28       TILTING
## 90643 2018-01-14 23:39:23       ON_FOOT
## 79169 2018-03-08 20:15:39         STILL</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        Plotting the frequency of Main Activities in Bangalore.
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">ggplot(activities.df, aes(x = main_activity, group = main_activity, fill = main_activity)) + 
  geom_bar()  + 
  guides(fill = &lt;span class="hljs-literal">FALSE&lt;/span>) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    x = &lt;span class="hljs-string">""&lt;/span>,
    y = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"Count"&lt;/span>,
    title = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"Main activities in Bangalore"&lt;/span>,
    caption = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"Associated activity for recorded positions in Bangalore. 
    Because Google records activity probabilities for each position, 
    only the activity with highest likelihood were chosen for each position."&lt;/span>
  )</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Filtering for transportation during coming to office only<br /> 1. Filtering for activities during working days only<br /> 2. Merging the travel data set(contains travel time)<br /> 3. Filtering for time between out.of.house.time and in.time (office in time)<br /> 4. On days where more than one means of transport is used, considering the one which was observed maximum number of times or using some logic.
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">transport &lt;- activities.df %&gt;% 
  filter((date(time) %&lt;span class="hljs-keyword">in&lt;/span>% date(attendance$Attendance.Date))) %&gt;% 
  mutate(date = date(time))
transport &lt;- merge(transport, travel, by = &lt;span class="hljs-string">'date'&lt;/span>) %&gt;% 
  filter(time &gt; out.of.house.time, time &lt; in.time.dmy.hm) %&gt;% 
  group_by(date, main_activity) %&gt;% 
  summarise(count = n()) %&gt;% 
  group_by(date) %&gt;%
  filter(main_activity %&lt;span class="hljs-keyword">in&lt;/span>% c(&lt;span class="hljs-string">"ON_BICYCLE"&lt;/span>, &lt;span class="hljs-string">"EXITING_VEHICLE"&lt;/span>, &lt;span class="hljs-string">'IN_VEHICLE'&lt;/span>,&lt;span class="hljs-string">"ON_FOOT"&lt;/span>)) %&gt;%
  top_n(&lt;span class="hljs-number">1&lt;/span>, count) %&gt;% 
  top_n(&lt;span class="hljs-number">1&lt;/span>, match(main_activity, c(&lt;span class="hljs-string">"ON_BICYCLE"&lt;/span>, &lt;span class="hljs-string">'IN_VEHICLE'&lt;/span>, &lt;span class="hljs-string">"EXITING_VEHICLE"&lt;/span>, &lt;span class="hljs-string">"ON_FOOT"&lt;/span>))) %&gt;%
  arrange(date)</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        The final data set will look as follows:
      </p>
      
      <pre><code class="hljs">##           date main_activity travelling.time
## 168 2018-08-17    IN_VEHICLE    731.287 secs
## 35  2018-01-18       ON_FOOT   1029.621 secs
## 30  2018-01-10       ON_FOOT    308.578 secs
## 190 2018-09-25    IN_VEHICLE    616.699 secs
## 198 2018-10-10    IN_VEHICLE   1501.639 secs</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        Plotting the frequencies of the means of transportation.
      </p>
      
      <pre class="r"><code class="hljs">ggplot(transport, aes(x = main_activity, group = main_activity, fill = main_activity)) + 
  geom_bar()  + 
  guides(fill = &lt;span class="hljs-literal">FALSE&lt;/span>) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    x = &lt;span class="hljs-string">""&lt;/span>,
    y = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"Count"&lt;/span>,
    title = &lt;span class="hljs-string">"Mode of transport"&lt;/span>
  )</code></pre>
      
      <p>
        <img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
      </p>
      
      <p>
        These variables travel time and mode of transportation will be used in another blog post to do analysis on office in-time.
      </p>
